        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down.</hi> | Beckenham | <hi rend="print">Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Sep. 27. 1869</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged for your extremely courteous letter, &amp; for your valuable notes together with the specimens.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>It is very good of you to take so much trouble for my sake.</p>
<p>I shall give several of your notes in any future edition of my work. The facts about grafting &amp; budding are perhaps the most important.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> But the case of the great difference in hardiness in the varieties of the Syringa Persica has particularly struck me. The varieties themselves are also very curious.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hooker of Kew happened to be staying here, &amp; I shewed him your specimens, several of which were new to him.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>With my best thanks for your very great kindness I beg leave to remain dear Sir | yours very faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6905.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Adolf Reuter, 23 September 1869</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Reuter’s experiments on grafting potatoes are mentioned in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7952.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, 1: 422, but this information is cited from a published source. Reuter did not mention potatoes in his notes with his letter of 23 September 1869.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD had mentioned <hi rend="italic">Syringa persica</hi> (Persian lilac) in <hi rend="italic">Varation</hi> 2: 164 in a discussion of the effects of climate on fertility. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6905.xml" resp="#automat" cert="medium">letter from Adolph Reuter, 23 September 1869</ref> and n. 8.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2357.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Joseph Dalton Hooker</ref> had arrived at Down on 25 September (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6908.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 24 September 1869</ref>).</note>
